description:
In this video essay I compare the hype to what’s really happening: burned-out teachers, iPad-raised kids who still can’t read, and a culture sliding into anti-intellectualism. Spoiler: software alone won’t solve systemic problems.

I am creating these videos for entertainment and educational purposes. Please do not contact or harass any individuals featured in the clips. These clips are included to critique broader trends in the tech industry, particularly where innovation is used to justify exploitative or user-unfriendly practices. I do not condone online bullying or harassment in any form. 

If you enjoyed this content, please consider subscribing to the channel!

All thoughts and opinions are my own. 

Chapters:
00:00 Intro
01:04 Tech CEO on AI and Education
03:52 Teachers: Kids Can't Read
06:40 Rise in Anti-intellectualism
10:10 Gen Alpha and iPad Kids
15:38 Parents Aren't Parenting
22:37 AI in the Classroom
26:43 Catness Says Hi

#TechnoSolutionism #TechCommentary #LiteracyCrisis #ArtificialIntelligence #Teachers

I have taught at TAFE and University college in Australia for over 22 years (so the age of my students were all late teens and adults) and have seen a MASSIVE drop in student capabilities. The most obvious change has been focus. Students are less focused and pay little attention. They want the qualification but don't want to put the effort into actually learning. The educational institutions I have worked for have supported this and allowed many to pass who have not developed skills or understanding. They only cared about the tuition fees. 

I left teaching almost 2 years ago because it was eroding my soul.

I’m a millennial parent with 3 alpha gen kids who, despite having special needs, are all A-advance students (very proud of them).  I truly believe an iPad can be a powerful tool—it just depends on how it’s used. That means as parents we have to stay on top of what our kids are doing and guide them along the way. Same goes for schools and teachers.
During lockdown, two of my kids ended up with teachers who honestly weren’t really teaching, so I pulled them out and homeschooled. Thankfully, we live in a time with so many amazing resources. I was able to use an eclectic approach—picking the best curriculum for each subject—which would have been extremely difficult pre-internet, due to time constraints.
When they returned to school, they were ahead of the curve. Was it hard? Absolutely. Was the sacrifice and loss of income worth it? 100%.
Parenting means being invested in your kids’ future. Lack of “village support” is hard and if you ever feel overwhelmed, please don’t be afraid to ask for help. If it happens to cost, it’s typically worth it—but remember, there are also tons of great free options out there. 🤓💜

comments.text:
When I started in the education system in the late 90’s, parents were partners. Now, they are entitled “bosses”  -  expecting but rarely contributing.
The school system spends more time and money on a “dog and pony show” & “eye wash” for the parents and the community. While we teachers spend our money on our students. We receive a pitiful tax break. The pay was the least of my issues. 

Also, in many schools, the number of students in a classroom is calculated based on the number of teachers. Consequently, as a 1st grade teacher, I’ve had up to 23 children with no assistance. My children’s kindergarten teacher did not have an assistant. 

The mother who was complaining about her child having to learn decimals is a prime example of these uneducated parents who rule the schools now. They can’t be bothered to work at home with their children so consequently don’t know what is being taught. 

I’ve worked with great teachers and useless ones, great parents and difficult ones but I place most of the blame on the system. A system created by folks who may have spent a small amount of time in the classroom eons ago but feel they know best.
comments.author: @Persimmons2000

I dunno, I mean, I'm a teacher, and I have not seen exclusively the type of things that you're outlining. I don't have such a dismal outlook on kids. Like I taught a summer camp this Summer at my local natural history museum to gen alpha kids (or whatever generation is K-8 now), and none of them had iPads. They were all playing. They were all excited to do hands on arts and crafts and they all learned and retained info like sponges. That's just what kids are like.

Now I'm teaching precalc to high school age kids and they are no more or less glued to screens than typical adults are. There's actually a law where I live that says kids in public school have to have their phones away during class or else teachers have to take them -- I find that's just unduly restrictive. Like most teachers I find the commands from on high are just didactic and make it harder for me to respond to my actual classroom. My students are upper classmen, they want independence, they want respect. They're 16, 17, 18. If they're done with their homework and they have an A and I have nothing else for them for the day, then for it to be mandated that I go and take their phone away is just gonna undermine my ability to build good relationships with my students. At this age they respect you and respect your authority much more if you rarely use it, and only when it's actually warranted. I think that law is just indicative of the mass hysteria around electronic devices.

And I mean, I have also used iPads educationally. I have used it with elementary aged kids to do IXL (online math curriculum) with a tutor. And yeah, they exhibit the "iPad kid" behaviors to an extent; they want to get on their games. But they are also in my experience willing to learn, and they also want to play legos and connect four and read a book with you and they like to draw and color. They're good, healthy kids. Kids are kids, they're always gonna be kids. And they're always gonna be the subject of "kids these days" complaints from adults that have forgotten their own problem behaviors when they were young.

AI could be useful but it will never replace human teachers. Kids need human adult mentors for psychosocial reasons. I can picture a classroom with maybe 25 kids online with their personalized AI tutors, and still, one teacher. Trying to replace teachers or increase the student teacher ratio with AI is a dystopian idea that might soon be tried, but it will never work in the long run.

comments.text:
You know what is also an issue in teaching? There's a ton of literature on didactics, but if you look at textbooks by larger publishers they often don't take into account this research. My experience as a chemistry teacher is very frustrating in this regard: the literature is for example very clear that when teaching the mole, you should NOT mention Avogadro's number. Maybe all the way at the end, but do try to avoid it. It's a very large number that by simple virtue of being large can be quite confusing, on top of it not really being used in secondary school chemistry. Anyway, what happens is that the large majority of textbooks START the chapter on the mole mole with Avogadro's number, showing very clearly they don't really put in the effort to improve their materials. But then you do receive e-mails as a teacher if you want to contribute for minimal to no pay to improve the textbooks. 

This also happens with those people who think AI can replace the teacher. They do not read the proper literature. One of the most important factors of learning is the quality of motivation in the child (not quantity, quality) - this has been proven multiple times in Self-Determination Theory literature. There are 3 ways to improve this, all of which should be catered to for good results: (perceived) competence --> not too difficult but also not too easy, (perceived) autonomy, and relation. For the last one, human interaction is instrumental and AI cannot replace that (there's also a part related to relevance to the student's personal life in relation btw). But also competence is important for humans to be there, as you can create an environment where the child feels supported and thus more confident to do things by themselves. Not to mention from a different part of literature: AI takes over a lot of work, while really doing the work is also important for learning. If you spend time looking something up, you get better at looking things up, but you also tend to remember better what you looked up. And then there's the whole social aspect of asking other students for answers or cheating off of them. We try to avoid the latter of course, but it is part of the social development of the child and AI will simply replace that.

I think it already went to far when schools started introducing laptops and iPads for secondary school students to be used in the classroom. Those are mainly just distractions. AI is even more detrimental if you ask me. 

Not a boomer btw, 29 y/o teacher with strong opinions on the state of the world, who's critical of 'developments' always being pictured as positively as possible, and who's worried that we're losing the most primal aspects of are human being (humanity itself) and how this may affect our capability of being happy on a societal level (there will always be people who can be happy, but I'm worried that the percentage of people who will have a lot of trouble to be actually happy may rise in the coming decades).

comments.text:
AI definitely has a place in education, no doubt about it. Let’s not kid ourselves—human teachers miss things. A lot of students fall through the cracks, and I was one of them.
Back when I was a teenager—over 50 years ago—I had a rough time with math in high school. I just couldn’t get it. I failed over and over, even went to summer school, and still bombed. What I really needed was someone to pull me aside, figure out what I did understand, and start from there. But that never happened. If you don’t get Grade 8 math, there’s no way you’re going to understand Grade 9 or 10. That’s just how it works.
Could I have told the teacher I didn’t get any of it? Maybe. But when you’re a kid, you don’t want to look dumb. Still, they should’ve picked up on it. They should’ve known something wasn’t clicking.
That’s why I think AI could be a game-changer. It doesn’t get tired, it doesn’t judge, and it can figure out exactly where you’re stuck. From there, it can help you in a ton of different ways—step by step, at your pace. I wish I’d had something like that back then. It might’ve made all the difference.
